  "prompt": "Can somebody explain how time is relative in layman's terms?",
  "response": "Absolutely! The idea that time is relative comes from Albert Einstein's theory of relativity. In layman's terms, it means that time isn't the same for everyone\u2014it depends on how fast you're moving or how strong gravity is around you.\n\nHere\u2019s a simple way to think about it:\n\n1. **Moving Fast Slows Down Time**: Imagine you\u2019re flying through space in a super-fast spaceship, close to the speed of light. To someone watching you from Earth, your clock would seem to tick slower than theirs. From your perspective, though, time would feel normal. This is called *time dilation*.\n\n2. **Gravity Affects Time**: The stronger the gravity, the slower time passes. For example, if you\u2019re standing on the surface of the Earth, time passes slightly slower for you compared to someone floating out in space where gravity is weaker. This is why clocks on satellites (which experience less gravity) run a tiny bit faster than clocks on Earth.\n\n3. **It\u2019s All About Perspective**: Time isn\u2019t a universal constant ticking the same way for everyone. It\u2019s flexible and depends on your speed and where you are in a gravitational field.\n\nTo sum it up: time is relative because it can \"stretch\" or \"shrink\" depending on how fast you\u2019re moving or how strong gravity is. It\u2019s a weird but fascinating part of how the universe works!",
